        <ul>
            <li>
                <h6>Brain training using cognitive apps can improve cognitive performance and processing speed in older
                    adults</h6>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-justify">Managing age-related decreases in cognitive function is an important public health
            challenge, especially in the context of the global ageing of the population. Over the last years, several
            Cognitive Mobile Games (CMG) have been developed to train and challenge the brain. However, currently, the
            level of evidence supporting the benefits of using CMG in real-life use is limited in older adults,
            especially at a late age. In this study, we analyzed game scores and the processing speed obtained over the
            course of 100 sessions in 12,000 subjects aged 60 to over 80 years. Users who trained with the games
            improved regardless of age in terms of scores and processing speed throughout the 100 sessions, suggesting
            that old and very old adults can improve their cognitive performance using CMG in real-life use.<br>
            <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8192763/">Visit site to read the paper.</a>
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li>
                <h6>A Large-Scale, Cross-Sectional Investigation Into the Efficacy of Brain Training
                </h6>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-justify">Brain training, a prominent industry, has sparked ongoing debates regarding its
            scientific foundation and efficacy. Existing evidence often stems from limited-scale studies lacking clarity
            on training specifics, transfer effects, and duration. To address this, we analyzed data from two large
            Internet-cohort studies (N = 60,222), examining cognition across various brain training methods and
            timeframes (circa 2010–2013). Results showed no cognitive benefits for brain training compared to other
            cognitive activities like computer or board games. However, nuanced analysis revealed a complex
            relationship: beginners showed lower cognitive baseline, while longer-term training correlated with improved
            working memory and verbal scores. Yet, no such improvement was observed in reasoning or self-reported
            everyday function. While brain training may offer benefits akin to trained tasks, effective cognitive
            enhancement may require longer training durations than previously studied.
            <br>
            <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6629869/">Visit site to read the paper.</a>
        </p>

